node.text:
“Perhaps most indelibly, Fanone offered his take on the rioters who’d heeded his pleas for mercy. “A lot of people have asked me my thoughts on the individuals in the crowd that helped me,” he drawled. “I think the conclusion I’ve come to is, like, thank you”—here he paused and squinted—“but f-ck you for being there.”

I posted the accompanying article from @time magazine, which is absolutely worth the read, on my Twitter @AGirlHasNoPres and in my stories.

This guy is wonderful and it makes me sick to my stomach when he talks about the things that he saw that day. The worst possible people stormed the Capitol on January 6th. Privileged, entitled, and presumptuous that they were just going to walk in and no one would try to stop them.

node.text:
***It literally takes a full minute, tops, to read the caption and know that these are not my words. Are you new here?***

Who wants to tell her? I guess you can lead a horse to water… God forbid you do something that could possibly prevent someone else from getting sick. Do these ppl not understand this is a private business? If a bakery doesn’t have to make a cake for a gay wedding, a business doesn’t have to let you in if you’re unvaccinated. 🤷🏻‍♀️ Like it or not, that’s their right. Stop begging for oppression. Ain’t nobody oppressing you! 

Y’all need to stop. You do too much. Having to wear a mask and being asked to get a vaccine to hopefully end a pandemic, is not comparable to what happened during segregation. It’s actually a pretty disgusting comparison. 

Earlier I saw someone compare having to wear a mask to Kristallnacht. Like, how? Why?? Stop. It’s gross, and it shows that you have no comprehension and or care or concern of what happened during segregation or Kristallnacht. #FauxPression
